nodes.title: Note // About
widgets_values:
Module #3 // Compositing & Editing v1.5 // About . . .
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
              >>>For Compositing and Editing<<<
---------------------------------------------------------------
---------------------------------------------------------------
This module handles a variety of tasks related to compositing and editing. New workflows are marked with an *, before their name in the list.
-------------------------------------------------------------
In-Paint: Right Click Load Image node, select "Open in MaskEditor", Clear Image, Mask area you want to change, and Save to Node. It is recommended to use an in-paint model.
-------------------------------------------------------------
ClipSeg: Auto mask portions of the image to edit via text input using this.
Github: https://github.com/time-river/ComfyUI-CLIPSeg
-------------------------------------------------------------
Pix2Pix: You can download the controlnet pix2pix model using the comfy-ui manager Install Models tab. More info:
https://github.com/timothybrooks/instruct-pix2pix
-------------------------------------------------------------
Simple Mask: a very basic way to create images using masks.
Example Mask IMGUR: https://imgur.com/a/6Osaw6v
-------------------------------------------------------------
IPAdapter Attention Masking: You can download the IPAdapters models using the comfy-ui manager Install Models tab. You will need a mask with blue, red, and green values to use this. Example Image Mask:
https://imgur.com/a/lfR8d2G
-------------------------------------------------------------
IPAdapter Styler: models available in Comfy-UI manager.
-------------------------------------------------------------
IpAdapter FaceID: models available in Comfy-UI manager.
-------------------------------------------------------------
*IpAdapter Composition: models available in Comfy-UI manager.
-------------------------------------------------------------
Image & Text Overlay: many options for overlays.
-------------------------------------------------------------
Image Cropping: a variety of ways to crop images.
-------------------------------------------------------------
Image Border: a variety of ways to make borders.
-------------------------------------------------------------
*Depth Imaging: create depth maps from images with ease.
Depth-fm: https://github.com/kijai/ComfyUI-depth-fm
-------------------------------------------------------------
*Big Lama Remover: mask what you want to remove in the image.
https://github.com/Layer-norm/comfyui-lama-remover 
-------------------------------------------------------------
Simple Mask: make images with masks or depth maps. Example Mask: https://imgur.com/a/6Osaw6v
-------------------------------------------------------------
*Layer Diffusion: creates transparent images on generate.
https://github.com/huchenlei/ComfyUI-layerdiffuse
-------------------------------------------------------------
*Differential Diffusion: a more powerful method of inpainting.
-------------------------------------------------------------
*IC-Light: re-light your images with controlable masks.
https://github.com/kijai/ComfyUI-IC-Light
-------------------------------------------------------------
*Alt. IC-Light: change the background lighting and scene.
https://github.com/huchenlei/ComfyUI-IC-Light-Native
-------------------------------------------------------------
*IC-Light Normals: Create normals from your images - I added this one late into the process so the setup is a bit more cramped than usual.
ttps://github.com/kijai/ComfyUI-IC-Light
-------------------------------------------------------------
*Post Processing: your basic post processing tools by Propost.
https://github.com/digitaljohn/comfyui-propost
-------------------------------------------------------------
*CatVTON: swap out the clothing on any person. Works well.
https://github.com/chflame163/ComfyUI_CatVTON_Wrapper
-------------------------------------------------------------
*Florence2: a text prompt auto-cropper.
https://github.com/spacepxl/ComfyUI-Florence-2
https://github.com/kijai/ComfyUI-Florence2
-------------------------------------------------------------
*SAM2 Point Seg: a new way to segment a section and crop it.
https://github.com/kijai/ComfyUI-segment-anything-2
https://github.com/neverbiasu/ComfyUI-SAM2
-------------------------------------------------------------
*SAM2 + Florence2: combines these two for auto-segmentation.
-------------------------------------------------------------
Node Color Information and More Below:

nodes.title: Note // Extra Information
widgets_values:
Module #3 // Compositing & Editing v1.5 // Extra Info . . .
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Website: https://aemotionstudio.org/
Youtube: https://www.youtube.com/@aemotionstudio
Civitai: https://civitai.com/user/AEmotionStudio
GitHub: https://github.com/AEmotionStudio
-------------------------------------------------------------
All modules here are uniform and have a left-to-right, top-to-bottom flow (sequential flow). Meaning they read just like a book. No nodes are hidden and all similar or branching nodes are grouped together accordingly. This aims to solve the organizational problem that most other workflows have and to simplify the creation process. All nodes are also color coded.
-------------------------------------------------------------
Main model used - Dreamshaper 8: 
https://civitai.com/models/4384?modelVersionId=128713
-------------------------------------------------------------
All IPAdapter models can be found in the Comfy UI Manager Install Models tab. Type "faceid" in the search for quick picks. Update all if you run into further issues.
-------------------------------------------------------------
For SDXL & LCM simply change models and parameters to match.
-------------------------------------------------------------
All groups are pinned - to unpin them - right click and select unpin while hovering over the group.
-------------------------------------------------------------

Module #3 // Image Cropping // Use this to crop Images // . . .
Module #3 // Image Border // Create borders for your images // . . .
Module #3 // Image & Text Overlay // Use this to overlay images & text // . . .
Module #3 // Filters & Color Correction // Add or Adjust Color // . . .
Module #3 // IPAdapter Styler // Use this to apply a style to your loaded image using the second image loader as the style combine // . . .
Module #3 // In-Paint // Manually inpaint your image - right click - Open in MaskEditor - clear image - mask area - save to nodes // . . .
Module #3 // IPAdapter Attention Masking // Use this to combine 3 images into a single image using attention masking for subject control // . . .
Module #3 // Pix2Pix // Use controlnet Pix2Pix & regular chat like language to convey the changes you want to make to the image // . . .
Module #3 // Differential Diffusion // Another more powerful method of inpainting - open MaskEditor and mask your image to use \\ . . .
Module #3 // Post Processing // Use this to add post effects to your images // . . .
Module #3 // Depth Imaging // Use this to create depth maps from images // . . .
Module #3 // Big Lama Remover // Remove objects by masking them in your image - works best with 512 x 512 resolution // . . .
Module #3 // ClipSeg // Use CLIPSeg to auto mask & modify specific parts of the image via text input // . . .
Module #3 // Florence2 // Use Florence2 model to auto-crop portions of an image via text input  // . . .
Module #3 // CatVTON // Use as a virtual try on application - auto-mask a section and replace clothing // . . .
Module #3 // SAM2 Point Seg // Uses SAM2 with point detection to crop sections of an image // . . .
Module #3 // IC-Light #1 // Use this to change the lighting in your images using a mask creation tool // . . .
Module #3 // IC-Light #3 // Use this to change the lighting in your images using a spline creation tool // . . .
